# Trivy ignore file for the apps/web container image scan.
# Scope: a SINGLE, documented, justified exception. Trivy still fails the build on every other
# CRITICAL/HIGH finding — the gate is NOT disabled and no rule is turned off.
#
# CVE-2026-33671 — picomatch: Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS), HIGH.
#
# Why it is accepted here and cannot be remediated via dependencies:
#   * The vulnerable picomatch@4.0.3 is VENDORED inside Next.js at
#     `next/dist/compiled/picomatch` — a copy Next bundles into its own distribution and ships in
#     the standalone output. Our own dependency tree is already patched: apps/web/package.json
#     pins picomatch via `overrides` to 4.0.4 and package-lock.json resolves 4.0.4 / 4.0.5. npm
#     overrides cannot reach a copy bundled inside Next's compiled output.
#   * picomatch is a build-time glob matcher. The ReDoS requires an attacker-controlled glob
#     pattern; at runtime the production server matches only trusted, developer-authored patterns
#     (next.config / middleware matchers), so untrusted input never reaches picomatch. It is not
#     exploitable by the running web server.
#   * Fixed upstream in picomatch >= 4.0.4. This exception clears automatically once Next ships a
#     release that bundles a patched picomatch — re-verify on every Next upgrade.
CVE-2026-33671
